  "prompt": "What is a ionic bond? What are some examples?",
  "response": "An ionic bond is a type of chemical bond formed through the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions. This occurs when one atom (usually a metal) loses one or more electrons to become a positively charged ion, known as a cation, while another atom (usually a non-metal) gains those electrons to become a negatively charged ion, known as an anion. The resulting attraction between the cations and anions holds the compounds together.\n\nIonic bonds typically form between elements that have a significant difference in electronegativity, enabling the transfer of electrons from one atom to another.\n\nExamples of ionic bonds include:\n\n1. **Sodium Chloride (NaCl)**: Sodium (Na) donates one electron to chlorine (Cl), resulting in the formation of a sodium ion (Na\u207a) and a chloride ion (Cl\u207b).\n2. **Magnesium Oxide (MgO)**: Magnesium (Mg) donates two electrons to oxygen (O), forming magnesium ions (Mg\u00b2\u207a) and oxide ions (O\u00b2\u207b).\n3. **Calcium Chloride (CaCl\u2082)**: Calcium (Ca) donates two electrons, one to each chlorine atom, forming calcium ions (Ca\u00b2\u207a) and chloride ions (Cl\u207b).\n4. **Potassium Bromide (KBr)**: Potassium (K) donates one electron to bromine (Br), resulting in potassium ions (K\u207a) and bromide ions (Br\u207b).\n\nThese compounds exhibit characteristics typical of ionic bonds, such as high melting and boiling points, and they often dissolve well in water, conducting electricity in their molten or dissolved states.",
